Various treatment options have been explored, however severe cases of ONJ still require surgical removal of the affected bone.<ref name="Bouquot1995">{{cite journal | author = Bouquot JE | coauthors = Christian J |title=Long-term effects of jawbone curettage on the pain of facial neuralgia |journal=J. Oral Maxillofac. Surg. |volume=53 |issue=4 |pages=387–97; discussion 397–9 |year=1995 |pmid=7699492 |doi=10.1016/0278-2391(95)90708-4}}</ref> A thorough history and assessement of pre-existing systemic problems and possible sites of dental infection are required to help prevent the condition, especially if bisphosphonate therapy is considered.<ref name="Woo2006"/>

